Graphics in R

R has an amazing ecosystem of graphing capabilities to produce static plots. As for dynamic/interactive plots, R is very limited, although there have been various packages developed in recent years to provide some interesting solutions.

In this session, we will focus on the most popular R package to create graphics: "ggplot2"

Introduction to ggplot2 (by Karthik Ram)

Walk through Karthik’s slides https://github.com/karthik/ggplot-lecture

Slides: https://github.com/karthik/ggplot-lecture/blob/master/ggplot.pdf

IRIS3

ggplot(data = iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width, color = Species)) + 
  geom_point() +
  facet_grid(. ~ Species) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c('blue', 'purple', 'green'))

ggplot(data = iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width, color = Species)) + 
  geom_point() +
  facet_grid(. ~ Species) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c('blue', 'purple', 'green')) +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm')

ggplot(data = iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width, color = Species)) + 
  geom_point(aes(shape = Species)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c('blue', 'purple', 'green')) +
  geom_smooth(method = 'loess')
